06016nam a22012015i 9781400866434DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008664347 a10.1515/97814008664342doi  a(DE-B1597)459957  a(OCoLC)984666046  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBP173.7b.S72 2017 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a320.55709642231 aSpiegel, Avi Max, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYoung Islam :bThe New Politics of Religion in Morocco and the Arab World /cAvi Max Spiegel.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPrinceton Studies in Muslim Politics ;v5700tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tA Note on Language -- tA Note on Anonymity -- tIntroduction ISLAMIST PLURALISM -- tPart I. RELATIONSHIPS -- tChapter 1. SHUTTLE ETHNOGRAPHY -- tChapter 2. COEVOLUTION -- tPart II. IDENTITIES -- tChapter 3. RANK AND FILE -- tChapter 4. WHAT YOUTH WANT -- tPart III. SHADOWS -- tChapter 5. UNHEARD VOICES OF DISSENT -- tChapter 6. REGULATING ISLAM -- tPart IV. INDIVIDUALS -- tChapter 7. EVERY RECRUITER IS A REINTERPRETER -- tChapter 8. SUITS AND DJELLABAS -- tChapter 9. STRATEGIZING THE SACRED -- tConclusion. THE NEXT ISLAMIST GENERATION -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tNOTES -- tINDEX -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aToday, two-thirds of all Arab Muslims are under the age of thirty. Young Islam takes readers inside the evolving competition for their support—a competition not simply between Islamism and the secular world, but between different and often conflicting visions of Islam itself.Drawing on extensive ethnographic research among rank-and-file activists in Morocco, Avi Spiegel shows how Islamist movements are encountering opposition from an unexpected source—each other. In vivid and compelling detail, he describes the conflicts that arise as Islamist groups vie with one another for new recruits, and the unprecedented fragmentation that occurs as members wrangle over a shared urbanized base. Looking carefully at how political Islam is lived, expressed, and understood by young people, Spiegel moves beyond the top-down focus of current research. Instead, he makes the compelling case that Islamist actors are shaped more by their relationships to each other than by their relationships to the state or even to religious ideology. By focusing not only on the texts of aging elites but also on the voices of diverse and sophisticated Muslim youths, Spiegel exposes the shifting and contested nature of Islamist movements today—movements that are being reimagined from the bottom up by young Islam.The first book to shed light on this new and uncharted era of Islamist pluralism in the Middle East and North Africa, Young Islam uncovers the rivalries that are redefining the next generation of political Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aIslam and politicszArab countries. 0aIslam and politicszMorocco. 0aMuslim youthzArab countries. 0aMuslim youthzMorocco. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh  aAl Adl wal Ihsan.  aArab Muslims.  aArab world.  aIslam.  aIslamism.  aIslamist groups.  aIslamist movements.  aIslamist organizations.  aIslamist pluralism.  aIslamists.  aJustice and Spirituality Organization.  aKing Mohammed VI.  aMorocco.  aMuslim youths.  aParty of Justice and Development.  aYassine.  aactivism.  aactivists.  aauthoritarian Arab state.  acoevolution.  afragmentation.  afunding.  aharaka.  apersonal empowerment.  apolitical Islam.  apolitical parties.  apolitical.  apower dynamics.  apr